\c 8
\s1 Ezra reads God’s instructions to the people
\p
\v 1 All the people gathered \add together in the plaza near\add* the Water Gate and \add asked\add* Ezra the scribe to bring the scroll with \add Yahweh’s instructions to Yisrael given through\add* Mosheh \add (Moses)\add*.
\v 2 \add So it was the beginning of October when\add* Ezra the priest brought the \add scroll\add* to the gathering of men and women and everyone who wanted to understand it,
\v 3 and he \add read it aloud in the plaza near\add* the Water Gate—reading from dawn until the middle of the day in front of those men and women and \add interested people, who all listened intently\add*.
\p
\v 4 Ezra the scribe stood on a raised wooden platform that they had made \add especially for this purpose\add*. Standing on his right were Mattitiah, Shema, Anayah, Uriyyah, Hilkiyyah, and Ma’aseyah, and on his left stood Pedayah, Misha’el, Malkiyyah, Hashum, Hashbaddanah, Zekaryah, and Meshullam.
\p
\v 5 \add Up on the platform,\add* Ezra opened the \add scroll in front\add* of all the people, and \add as he did so\add*, all the people stood up.
\v 6 Ezra blessed the great God Yahweh and the people \add raised their arms and responded\add*, “May it be so.” Then they knelt down and bowed to Yahweh \add with their faces\add* to the ground.
\p
\v 7 Then Yeshua, Bani, Shereveyah, Yamin, Akkub, Shabtai, Hodiyyah, Ma’aseyah, Kelita, Azaryah, Yozavad, Hanan, Pelayah, who were all Levites, \add explained what had been read\add* to the people standing there.
\v 8 They read the scroll containing God’s instructions, \add explaining how it applied so\add* the people could understand \add it\add*.
\p
\v 9 Then Nehemyah the governor and Ezra the priest & scribe, and the Levites who were \add explaining it\add*, said to all the people, “Today is a sacred day—it belongs to your god Yahweh. Don’t mourn or weep.” \add That was\add* because all the people were weeping after they heard \add Yahweh’s instructions to them\add*.
\v 10 Then \add Nehemyah\add* told them, “Go \add home and\add* eat \add some special food with sweet drink\add*, and \add share some with\add* those \add who can’t afford such things\add* because today is \add a sacred day that\add* belongs to our master. And don’t grieve, because \add the happiness from Yahweh will make you all strong\add*.”
\p
\v 11 The Levites \add told the people to quieten down\add*, saying, “\add Don’t grieve today because it’s a sacred day. Stay quiet.\add*”
\v 12 \add So\add* all the people went to eat and drink and to \add take plates of food to others\add*, and to \add have a big celebration\add* because they understood what \add had been read\add* to them.
\s1 The celebration in shelters
\p
\v 13 The \add next\add* day, \add all the clan leaders\add*, and the priests and Levites, met with Ezra the scribe to \add study the instructions\add* \add on the scroll\add*.
\v 14 They \add discovered that it was\add* written in the \add instructions that Yahweh had given through Mosheh\add*, that the Israelis should live in \add temporary\add* shelters during the celebration in their seventh month \add (our September-October)\add*.\x + \xo 8:14-15: \xt Lev 23:33-36,39-43; Deu 16:13-15.\x*
\v 15 They should \add publicly proclaim\add* in Yerushalem and in all their towns \add that the people should go into the hills and bring back branches from olive or wild olive trees, myrtle or palm trees, and/or other\add* leafy trees to make shelters as it’s written.
\p
\v 16 \add So\add* the people went out and brought \add back branches\add* to make shelters for themselves on their roofs or in their courtyards, or in the temple courtyard or in the plazas near the Water Gate and the Efrayim Gate.
\v 17 Then the whole assembly \add of people\add* who’d come back from captivity made shelters and lived in them \add for one week\add*. The \add Israelis\add* hadn’t done that since the \add time of Yehoshua’s leadership\add*, and \add they did it with a lot of celebration\add*.
\v 18 \add Ezra\add* read aloud from the scroll of God’s instructions each day of the seven days of celebration, then on the eighth day they all gathered together as per the instructions.
\c 9
\s1 The people confess their sins
\p
\v 1 On the 24th of that month, the \add Israelis dressed in sackcloth, put dust on their heads, fasted, and gathered together\add*.
\v 2 Those of \add Jewish descent stood separately\add* from the descendants of foreigners, and they confessed their \add own\add* sins, as well as those of their ancestors.
\v 3 They stood and \add listened to the scroll with Yahweh’s instructions being read for three hours\add*, then for \add another three hours\add* they confessed and bowed down to Yahweh their god.
\v 4 Then Yeshua went up the Levites’ stairs with Bani, Kadmi’el, Shevanyah, Bunni, Shereveyah, \add another\add* Bani, \add and\add* Kenani, and they called out loudly to their God Yahweh.
\p
\v 5 Then \add some\add* Levites (Yeshua, Kadmi’el, Bani, Hashavneyah, Shereveyah, Hodiyyah, Shevanyah, and Petahyah) said, “\add Stand\add* up \add and\add* bless your eternal God Yahweh: May \add the peoples\add* bless your \add wonderful reputation\add* which is \add greater than anything else that we bless or praise\add*.
\v 6 Yahweh, you alone are \add God\add*. You yourself made the heavens, the \add galaxies in\add* the heavens and all their \add stars\add*, the earth and all that is on it, the seas and all that is in them. You \add give life to everything\add*, and \add all the stars bow down\add* to you.
\p
\v 7 “You are Yahweh, the god who chose Abram. Then you brought him out from Ur in the \add Chaldean region\add*, then you \add renamed him to\add* Abraham \add (meaning ‘father of many’)\add*.
\v 8 You \add discovered that he was sincere and faithful to you, and made an agreement with him\add*—to give the Canaanite, Hittite, Amorite, Perizzite, Yebusite, and the Girgashite \add regions\add* to his descendants, and you have \add ensured that it’s all come to be\add* because you’re righteous.\x + \xo 9:8: \xt Gen 15:18-21.\x*
\v 9 You \add noticed the suffering\add* of our ancestors \add enslaved\add* in Egypt, and then you heard their cry \add for help\add* \add at the edge of\add* the Red Sea.
\p
\v 10 “You \add displayed miracles\add* to Far-oh \add (Pharaoh)\add*, and to all his servants and to all the \add Egyptian\add* people, because you knew that they were acting \add as if you weren’t real\add*, \add so you got yourself a reputation which you still have to\add* this day.\x + \xo 9:10: \xt Exo 7:8–12:32.\x*
\v 11 Then you split the sea open the sea \add right in front of their eyes\add*, and they \add walked\add* through the middle of \add it\add* on dry land. \add After that,\add* you \add drowned\add* their pursuers into the \add deep sea\add* like a stone in \add a huge lake\add*.\x + \xo 9:11: a \xt Exo 14:21-29; \xo b \xt Exo 15:4-5.\x*
\v 12 You led them \add during the\add* day with a pillar of cloud, and \add during the\add* night with a pillar of fire to illuminate the way that they should go.\x + \xo 9:12: \xt Exo 13:21-22.\x*
\p
\v 13 “Then you came down to Mt. Sinai and spoke with them from the sky, and you gave to them \add principles of justice\add* and laws of truth—good statutes and instructions.\x + \xo 9:13-14: \xt Exo 19:18–23:33.\x*
\v 14 You \add revealed the concept of a rest day\add* to them, and you \add gave\add* them rules and instructions and laws via your servant Mosheh \add (Moses)\add*.
\p
\v 15 “You gave them bread from the sky \add when they were hungry\add*, and you \add made\add* water \add come out of a rock when they were thirsty\add*, then \add eventually\add* you told them to go \add ahead\add* to possess the land that you had \add said that you’d\add* give to them.\x + \xo 9:15: a \xt Exo 16:4-15; \xo b \xt Exo 17:1-7; \xo c \xt Deu 1:21.\x*
\p
\v 16 “\add But\add* our ancestors \add were proud and stubborn\add* and they \add refused to obey your instructions\add*.\x + \xo 9:16-17: \xt Num 14:1-4; Deu 1:26-33.\x*
\v 17 \add Not only did they refuse to listen\add*, they \add forgot about all the miracles that you’d done for\add* them and they \add became stubborn\add* and appointed a leader to take them back to their slavery. \add But\add* you are a god of forgiveness—gracious and compassionate, \add slow to get angry\add* and \add generously showing loyal affection\add*, and you didn’t abandon them.\x + \xo 9:17: \xt Exo 34:6; Num 14:18.\x*
\v 18 Even when they \add molded a metal\add* calf for themselves and said, ‘This is your god who brought you \add out of\add* Egypt’, and they \add badly insulted you\add*,\x + \xo 9:18: \xt Exo 32:1-4.\x*
\v 19 you didn’t abandon them in the wilderness \add because you’re so merciful\add*. \add You didn’t remove\add* the pillar of cloud that led them on the way \add during the\add* day, or \add remove\add* the pillar of fire that shone at night for them \add to show them\add* which way they should go.\x + \xo 9:19-21: \xt Deu 8:2-4.\x*
\v 20 You gave them your good spirit to give them insight. You didn’t withhold your manna \add for them to eat\add*, and you \add still\add* gave them water \add to drink\add*,
\v 21 \add yes,\add* you sustained them in the wilderness for forty years—they \add had everything they needed\add*—their clothes didn’t wear out, and their feet didn’t swell.
\p
\v 22 “Then you \add handed kingdoms and people groups over to\add* them, and you \add let them settle in even the far corners of the regions\add*. They took possession of the King Sihon’s Heshbon \add region\add*, and King Og’s Bashan \add region\add*.\x + \xo 9:22: \xt Num 21:21-35.\x*
\v 23 You \add gave our ancestors lots of children so\add* they were like the \add many\add* stars in the sky, then you brought them into this land which you’d told their ancestors to enter and \add take ownership of\add*.\x + \xo 9:23: a \xt Gen 15:5; 22:17; \xo b \xt Josh 3:14-17.\x*
\v 24 Their children went in and \add took over\add* the land \add after you went ahead of them and\add* subdued the \add previous\add* inhabitants, the Canaanites. You \add allowed them to defeat\add* them and their kings, and the people groups in the land—\add letting them do whatever they wanted\add* to do with them.\x + \xo 9:24: \xt Josh 11:23.\x*
\v 25 They captured fortified cities and \add productive land\add*, and they \add took over\add* houses full of all good things, \add stone\add* cisterns, vineyards and olive orchards, and \add lots of\add* fruit trees. They ate and were satisfied, and grew fat and \add enjoyed themselves as a result of your amazing\add* goodness.\x + \xo 9:25: \xt Deu 6:10-11.\x*
\p
\v 26 “\add But\add* they disobeyed and rebelled against you, and they \add turned their backs on your instructions\add*. They killed your prophets who testified against them in order to bring them back to you and they \add badly insulted you\add*.\x + \xo 9:26-28: \xt Jdg 2:11-16.\x*
\v 27 \add So\add* you \add allowed their enemies to harass and conquer\add* them. Then in the time of their distress, they cried out to you, and you yourself heard from heaven. \add Because you’re so merciful\add*, you \add sent\add* saviours to them who rescued them from their enemies.
\v 28 After \add they’d returned to an era of peace\add*, they reverted to doing evil \add again in front of you\add* and you left them to \add submit to\add* their enemies and \add the oppression that followed\add*. Then they’d return and cry out to you, and you heard from heaven and delivered them many times \add because you’re merciful\add*.
\v 29 You \add showed them their errors so they’d return to following your instructions, but instead they ignored you\add* and didn’t \add obey your commands\add*. \add They ignored your values which would have helped them if they’d lived\add* by them and they turned a stubborn shoulder, stiffened their necks, and \add refused to listen\add*.\x + \xo 9:29: \xt Lev 18:5.\x*
\v 30 \add Yet\add* you \add put up\add* with them for many years, and you testified against them with your spirit \add through the messages\add* of your prophets, but they \add still\add* didn’t \add take any notice, so\add* you \add allowed the other people groups to conquer\add* them.\x + \xo 9:30: \xt 2Ki 17:13-18; 2Ch 36:15-16.\x*
\v 31 \add However, because you’re so merciful\add*, you didn’t abandon them and you didn’t \add wipe them out completely\add*. \add Yes,\add* you’re a god who’s gracious and merciful.
\p
\v 32 “\add So now\add* God, our amazing, powerful, and awesome God who keeps \add his agreements due to his\add* loyal commitment, don’t \add just ignore all our current hardships affecting\add* us, our kings and our leaders, our priests and our prophets, and our ancestors and all your people, from the \add period\add* of the Assyrian kings until today.\x + \xo 9:32: \xt 2Ki 15:19-29; 17:3-6; Ezr 4:2,10.\x*
\v 33 You are \add totally fair in allowing all that to happen to\add* us, because you have behaved faithfully, but \add in contrast\add*, we have behaved wickedly—
\v 34 and our kings, our leaders, our priests, and our ancestors haven’t \add obeyed your instructions\add* and they haven’t \add bothered with following\add* your commands or \add taking notice of\add* your \add complaints that you made know to\add* them.
\v 35 \add They served in their own kingdom and enjoyed the incredible goodness that you poured on\add* them and the wide and prosperous land that you gave them, \add but\add* they didn’t serve you, and they didn’t turn away from their evil actions.
\p
\v 36 “\add Take notice of\add* us today—we’re servants, and the land that you gave to our ancestors \add so we could\add* eat its fruit and its produce, \add but look at us now\add*—we’re servants in \add our own land\add*.
\v 37 \add Now\add* its plentiful produce belongs to the kings who \add you’ve placed over us due to\add* our sins, and who rule over our bodies and over our livestock \add just however they want to, so\add* we’re \add terribly distressed\add*.
\p
\v 38 “\add So now\add* in all of this, we’re \add faithfully making an agreement\add*, and our leaders, our Levites, and our priests will even write it down on a document \add and sign it\add*.”
