\s1 The agreement
\p
\v 28 The rest of the people, the priests, the Levites, the gatekeepers, the \add singers\add*, the gatekeepers, and all the \add people who were prepared to dedicate themselves to obeying God rather than the customs of the former inhabitants of the land\add*, their wives, their sons and their daughters, \add and\add* \add everyone who was old enough to understand\add*,
\v 29 were \add joining with\add* their brothers, their nobles, and were \add committing to a promise which also had\add* a curse: to \add obey God’s instructions as\add* given by God’s servant Mosheh, and to keep and to do all the commands of Yahweh our master, \add accepting\add* his judgements and his statutes.
\p
\v 30 \add They committed to\add* not giving their daughters to the \add other\add* \add people groups\add* in the land, and to not taking their daughters for their sons.\x + \xo 10:30: \xt Exo 34:16; Deu 7:3.\x*
\p
\v 31 On the rest day or \add other\add* holy day, we won’t \add buy goods or grain\add* from the peoples of the land (even if they bring it to sell it to us), and we \add won’t plant or harvest, or reclaim debts, in\add* the seventh year.\x + \xo 10:31: a \xt Exo 23:10-11; Lev 25:1-7; \xo b \xt Deu 15:1-2.\x*
\p
\v 32 We \add will also pledge to each donate a week’s wages each year to support the temple functions\add*\x + \xo 10:32: \xt Exo 30:11-16.\x*
\v 33 \add including\add* the bread \add displayed\add* in rows, the continual offering and the continual burnt offering, for the rest day \add offerings\add* and the new moons, for the appointed times and for the holy things, for the sin offerings to cover over Yisrael’s \add guilt\add*, and for all the \add operation\add* of God’s residence.
\p
\v 34 Then we \add threw dice\add* \add to choose from\add* among the priests, the Levites, and the people \add to create the roster for\add* bringing \add firewood to the temple as an\add* offering \add to be used\add* at the appointed times \add each\add* year for burning on the altar of Yahweh our God as written in the \add scrolls\add*.
\p
\v 35 Every year \add we will also\add* bring the \add early produce from\add* our soil and the \add first harvest from\add* every fruit tree to Yahweh’s \add temple\add*.\x + \xo 10:35: \xt Exo 23:19; 34:26; Deu 26:2.\x*
\v 36 We will \add dedicate\add* our \add eldest male\add* sons \add at the temple\add*, and bring the eldest offspring of our herds and our flocks to the priests who serve at God’s \add residence\add*.\x + \xo 10:36: \xt Exo 13:2.\x*
\p
\v 37 We will bring our offerings and the first of our flour, and the fruit of every tree, wine, and oil, for the priests, to the \add temple storerooms\add*, and a tenth of our \add produce\add* for the Levites.
\p The Levites will be the ones receiving a tenth \add of our cash income\add* in all the towns \add where we work\add*.\x + \xo 10:37: \xt Num 18:21.\x*
\v 38 A priest who’s a descendant of Aharon must be with \add them\add* when they collect the tenths, then the Levites must take a tenth of that to the \add temple\add* to be placed in their treasury rooms.\x + \xo 10:38: \xt Num 18:26.\x*
\v 39 The \add Israelis\add* and the \add Levites\add* must bring the offerings of grain, wine, and oil to the storerooms. There must \add also\add* be \add utensils\add* for the sanctuary and the priests, for the ones who are ministering and the gatekeepers, and for the \add singers\add*.
\p We mustn’t neglect our god’s house.
\c 11
\s1 The people living in Yerushalem
\p
\v 1 The people’s leaders lived in Yerushalem, \add but\add* the rest of the people \add drew straws\add* to select one out of ten \add families\add* to reside in Yerushalem the holy city—\add the other nine settled in the towns\add*,
\v 2 then the people blessed the ones who’d freely offered to live there in Yerushalem.
\v 3 In the towns in Yehudah, everyone lived on their own property. That included the Israelis, the priests and Levites, the temple servants, and the descendants of Shelomoh’s servants. The provincial officials lived in Yerushalem,\x + \xo 11:3-4: \xt Neh 7:73.\x*
\v 4 \add as well as\add* some of Yehudah’s and Benyamin’s descendants.
\p Yehudah’s descendants \add in Yerushalem included\add*:
\li1 Atayah (son of Uzziyah, son of Zekaryah, son of Amaryah, son of Shefatyah, son of Mahalalel, a descendant of Ferets),
\li1
\v 5 Ma’aseyah (son of Baruk, son of Kol-Hozeh, son of Hazayah, son of Adayah, son of Yoyariv, son of Zekaryah, son of Shiloni).
\m
\v 6 \add Altogether\add* 468 strong men who were Ferets’ descendants lived in Yerushalem.
\p
\v 7 Benyamin’s descendants \add in Yerushalem included\add*:
\li1 Sallu (son of Meshullam, son of Yoed, son of Pedayah, son of Kolayah, son of Ma’aseyah, son of Iti’el, son of Yeshayah).
\li1
\v 8 Gabay \add and\add* Sallay.
\m A total of 928.
\v 9 Zikri’s son Yoel was their overseer in the city, and Hassenuah’s son Yihudah was his second-in-command.
\p
\v 10 The priests \add in Yerushalem included\add*:
\li1 Yoyariv’s son Yedayah \add and\add* Yakin,
\li1
\v 11 Serayah (son of Hilkiyyah, son of Meshullam, son of Tsadok, son of Merayot, son of Ahituv) \add who was the leader in the temple\add*.
\v 12 \add There were 822 of them when\add* their brothers who work in the \add temple\add* \add were included\add*.
\li1 Adayah (son of Yeroham, son of Pelalyah, son of Amtsi, son of Zekaryah, son of Pashhur, son of Malkiyyah).
\v 13 \add There were 242 of them when\add* their brothers and family heads \add were included\add*.
\li1 Amashsai (son of Azar’el, son of Ahzai, son of Meshillemot, son of Immer),
\v 14 and his brothers who were strong warriors, \add came to a total of\add* 128.
\m Haggedolim’s son Zavdi’el was their overseer.
\p
\v 15 The Levites \add in Yerushalem included\add*:
\li1 Shemayah (son of Hasshuv, son of Azrikam, son of Hashavyah, son of Bunni),
\li1
\v 16 Shabbetai and Yozavad from the Levite leaders who \add supervised\add* the work outside the \add temple\add*,
\li1
\v 17 Mattanyah (son of Mikah, son of Zavdi, son of Asaf) the leader who offered the thanksgiving prayer,
\li1 Bakbukyah \add who was the assistant leader\add*, and Avda (son of Shammua, son of Galal, the son of Yedutun).
\m
\v 18 The \add total number\add* of Levites in the sacred city were 284.
\p
\v 19 The gatekeepers \add in Yerushalem included\add*:
\li1 Akkuv, Talmon, and their brothers.
\m A total of 172.
\p
\v 20 The rest of Yisrael \add and\add* the \add other\add* priests \add and\add* Levites, all \add lived\add* their \add ancestral\add* towns across Yehudah.
\v 21 The temple workers lived on Ofel \add hill\add*, and Tsiha and Gishpa \add supervised\add* \add them\add*.
\p
\v 22 The overseer of the Levites in Yerushalem was Uzzi (son of Bani, son of Hashavyah, son of Mattanyah, son of Mika)—a descendant of Asaf’s sons who were the \add temple singers\add*
\v 23 because the \add Persian\add* king had ordered that the singers should have \add daily\add* provisions \add supplied\add*.
\p
\v 24 Petahyah (son of Meshezavel, from the sons of Zerah, the son of Yehudah) was \add the intermediary with the king for any matter that the people raised\add*.
\s1 The people in other cities and towns
\p
\v 25 \add Most\add* of Yehudah’s descendants \add settled in the villages with their fields nearby\add*: in Kiryat-Arba and the surrounding villages, in Divon and the surrounding villages, and in Yekavtse’el and the surrounding villages,
\v 26 in Yeshua, in Moladah, and in Beyt-Pelet,
\v 27 in Hatsar-Shual, and in Be’er-Sheva and the surrounding villages,
\v 28 in Tsiklag, and in Mekonah and the surrounding villages,
\v 29 in Eyn-Rimmon, in Tsorah, and in Yarmut,
\v 30 in Zanoah \add and\add* Adullam and their villages, in Azekah and its villages. \add So\add* they settled from Be’er-Sheva \add all the way\add* to the Hinnom valley.
\p
\v 31 Benyamin’s descendants settled in Geva, Mikmas, Ayyah, and Beyt-El and its villages,
\v 32 \add in\add* Anatot, Nov, \add and\add* Anayah,
\v 33 \add in\add* Hatsor, Ramah, \add and\add* Gittayim,
\v 34 \add in\add* Hadid, Tsevoim, \add and\add* Nevallat,
\v 35 \add in\add* Lod, Ono, \add and in\add* the Craftsmen’s valley.
\v 36 \add Also\add* some Levites \add previously\add* \add connected with\add* Yehudah \add settled\add* in Benyamin.
\c 12
\s1 The priests and Levites
\p
\v 1 These are the priests and the Levites who came \add back\add* with Shealtiyel’s son Zerubavel and with Yeshua:
\li1 Serayah, Yermeyah, \add and\add* Ezra,
\li1
\v 2 Amaryah, Malluk, \add and\add* Hattush,
\li1
\v 3 Shekanyah, Rehum, \add and\add* Meremot,
\li1
\v 4 Iddo, Ginneton, \add and\add* Aviyyah,
\li1
\v 5 Miyyamin, Moadyah, \add and\add* Bilgah,
\li1
\v 6 Shemayah, Yoyariv, \add and\add* Yedayah,
\li1
\v 7 Sallu, Amok, Hilkiyyah, \add and another\add* Yedayah.
\m Those were the leaders of the priests and their brothers in Yeshua’s time.
\p
\v 8 The Levites \add were\add*:
\li1 Yeshua, Binnui, Kadmiel, Shereveyah, Yehudah, \add and\add* Mattanyah \add who led\add* the thanksgiving songs \add along with\add* his brothers,
\li1
\v 9 Bakbukyah and Unni—their brothers who \add stood\add* opposite them in the \add services\add*.
\s1 The high priest Yeshua’s descendants
\p
\v 10 Yeshua fathered Yoyakim who then fathered Elyashiv, and Elyashiv fathered Yoyada.
\v 11 Then Yoyada fathered Yonatan who then fathered Yaddua.
\s1 Leaders of priestly families
\p
\v 12 In Yoyakim’s \add time\add*, these were the heads of the priestly families:
\li1 Merayah \add was the head\add* of Serayah’s \add family\add*,
\li1 Hananyah for Yirmeyah’s,
\li1
\v 13 Meshullam for Ezra’s \add family\add*,
\li1 Yehohanan for Amaryah’s,
\li1
\v 14 Yonatan for Malluk’s \add family\add*,
\li1 Yosef for Shevanyah’s,
\li1
\v 15 Adna for Harim’s \add family\add*,
\li1 Helkai for Merayot’s,
\li1
\v 16 Zekaryah for Iddo’s \add family\add*,
\li1 Meshullam for Ginneton’s,
\li1
\v 17 Zikri for Aviyyah’s \add family\add*,
\li1 Filtai for Moadyah’s,
\li1
\v 18 Shammua for Bilgah’s \add family\add*,
\li1 Yonatan for Shemayah’s,
\li1
\v 19 Mattenai for Yoyariv’s \add family\add*,
\li1 Uzzi for Yedayah’s,
\li1
\v 20 Kallai for Sallai’s \add family\add*,
\li1 Ever for Amok’s,
\li1
\v 21 Hashavyah for Hilkiyyah’s \add family\add*,
\li1 \add and\add* Netan’el for Yedayah’s.
\s1 The records of priests and Levites
\p
\v 22 In the days of Elyashiv, Yoyada, Yohanan, and Yaddua, during the reign of Persian \add King\add* Darius, the heads of the families of the Levites and priests were recorded.
\v 23 \add The names of\add* the descendants of Levi who were heads of families were written in the \add official history records\add* up till the time of Elyashiv’s son Yohanan.
\s1 Various helper roles in the temple
\p
\v 24 The Levites’ leaders were Hashavyah, Shereveyah, and Kadmiel’s son Yeshua with their brothers serving opposite them \add in each service\add* to praise and give thanks as had been commanded by David, the man of God.
\p
\v 25 Mattanyah, Bakbukyah, Ovadyah, Meshullam, Talmon, and Akkuv were gatekeepers who \add stood\add* guard at the storerooms near the \add temple\add* gates.
\p
\v 26 That was at the \add time\add* of Yoyakim (son of Yeshua, son of Yotsadak), and at the \add time\add* of Nehemyah the governor and Ezra the priest and scribe.
\s1 The dedication of Yerushalem’s wall
\p
\v 27 At the dedication of the wall \add around\add* Yerushalem, they \add summoned\add* Levites from all \add over the region\add* to come to Yerushalem to perform the dedication with rejoicing and thanksgiving, and with \add musical instruments and singing\add*,
\v 28 \add plus the next generation\add* of singers came both from Yerushalem and its surrounds, and from the Netofati villages.
\v 29 \add They also\add* \add came\add* from Beyt-Gilgal, and from the fields of Geva and Azmavet, because the singers had built villages near Yerushalem to live in.
\v 30 The priests and Levites \add held a purification ceremony for\add* themselves, then they purified the people and the gates and the wall.
\p
\v 31 Then I \add assembled\add* Yehudah’s leaders together up on top of the wall, and I \add assigned\add* them into two large groups \add who would give thanks\add* \add as they walked around it\add*.
\p \add The first group\add* headed towards the Dung Gate on the right.
\v 32 Hoshayah and half of Yehudah’s officials \add were in that group\add*
\v 33 \add along with\add* Azaryah, Ezra, and Meshullam,
\v 34 Yehudah, Benyamin, Shemayah, and Yirmeyah,
\v 35 plus some of the \add next generation\add* of priests with trumpets: Zekaryah (son of Yonatan, son of Shemayah, son of Mattanyah, son of Mikayah, son of Zakkur, son of Asaf)
\v 36 and his brothers Shemayah, Azar’el, Milalai, Gilalai, Ma’ai, Nethan’el, Yehudah, \add and\add* Hanani. \add They used\add* the instruments \add as per the instructions\add* of \add the late King\add* David, the man of God. Ezra the scribe \add went in front of them\add*.
\v 37 When they got to the Fountain Gate, they went up the stairs at the City of David, \add and along the higher portion of the wall by David’s palace\add* as far as the Water Gate (\add on the east\add* \add side of the city\add*).
\p
\v 38 The \add other group giving thanks\add* with the other half of the people went in the opposite direction \add around the top of the wall\add*—going past the Tower of the Ovens to the \add wider part\add* of the wall.
\v 39 \add We passed\add* Efrayim Gate, the Old Gate, Fish Gate, and Hananel Tower, the Tower of the Hundred, \add and all the way to\add* the Sheep Gate, and we \add stopped at\add* the Guard Gate.
\p
\v 40 Then \add both\add* groups \add ended up at the temple\add* and stood there. I was there with the half of the city officials who’d \add accompanied\add* me,
\v 41 \add as well as\add* the priests with their trumpets: Elyakim, Ma’aseyah, Minyamin, Mikayah, Elyeoenai, Zekaryah, Hanayah,
\v 42 \add another\add* Ma’aseyah, Shemayah, El’azar, Uzzi, Yehohanan, Malkiyyah, Eylam, and Ezer. The singers sang loudly with their leader Yizrahyah.
\p
\v 43 Then that \add same\add* day they offered many sacrifices, and they \add celebrated\add* because God had made them very pleased. The women and children also celebrated, \add in fact\add* the sound of the celebrations in Yerushalem was so loud that it can be heard far away.
\s1 Supporting the temple operation
\p
\v 44 Then \add still on\add* that \add same\add* day, men were appointed \add to be in charge of the storerooms\add* for the tithes and offerings. The \add percentages\add* for the priests and the Levites were gathered from the fields around the cities as per the \add written\add* law, because \add the people of\add* Yehudah \add were happy to have\add* the priests and the Levites \add serving\add*.
\v 45 They \add served God with their daily duties and the purification ceremonies\add*, as well as \add the duties of\add* the singers and gatekeepers—\add all done according to the instructions\add* \add left by King\add* David and his son Shelomoh,\x + \xo 12:45: a \xt 1Ch 25:1-8; \xo b \xt 1Ch 26:12.\x*
\v 46 because it was \add handed down\add* from the original singers who sang songs of praise and thanksgiving to God in the time of David and Asaf.
\v 47 In Zerubavel and Nehemyah’s times, all Yisrael \add contributed the daily food allowance\add* for the singers and gatekeepers. They \add also gave a percentage\add* to the Levites \add who then gave a percentage of that\add* to \add the priests\add* (Aharon’s descendants).
\c 13
\s1 Separating out the foreigners
\p
\v 1 That day, the \add Mosheh scroll was read out aloud to\add* the people, and it was \add discovered that it had been written that no Ammonite or Moabite is ever allowed to join the congregation\add*\x + \xo 13:1-2: \xt Deu 23:3-5.\x*
\v 2 because \add instead of helping the travelling Israelis with food\add* and water, they had hired Bil’am \add (Balaam)\add* to curse them (even though God had turned that curse into blessing).\x + \xo 13:2: \xt Num 22:1-6.\x*
\v 3 \add After\add* hearing \add that\add*, they separated out all of \add the foreigners\add*.
\s1 Nehemyah’s reforms
\p
\v 4 \add Prior to that time,\add* the high priest Elyashiv (closely related to Toviyyah) had been in charge of the \add temple storerooms\add*
\v 5 and he’d \add allowed\add* \add Toviyyah\add* to have a large room that had previously been used to store offerings: the frankincense, the utensils, and \add donated\add* grain, wine, and oil, (the percentage commanded \add to be given to\add* the Levites, the singers, and the gatekeepers), and the offerings for the priests.
\v 6 \add During all that period,\add* I hadn’t been in Yerushalem because I’d returned to the Babylonian king in the 32nd year of Artahshashta’s reign \add (Artaxerxes)\add*. \add However, after a while\add* I requested leave \add again\add* from the king
\v 7 and I came \add back\add* to Yerushalem. \add It was then that\add* \add I discovered how\add* evil Elyashiv had been by making a storeroom for Toviyyah in the courts of God’s residence.
\v 8 \add It made me very upset\add* and I threw everything of Toviyyah’s out of the room.
\v 9 Then I \add ordered the storerooms to be purified\add* \add by the priests\add* \add before\add* I returned the \add temple utensils\add* to the room, along with the grain offerings and the incense.
\p
\v 10 I \add found out\add* that the Levites and the singers weren’t being given their percentage, \add so they’d left their duties and\add* returned to \add cultivate\add* their own fields.\x + \xo 13:10: \xt Deu 12:19.\x*
\v 11 I \add made a complaint to\add* the officials asking why the \add operation of the temple had been neglected\add*, and then I \add rounded up\add* \add the Levites and the singers\add* and \add sent them back to their duties\add*.
\v 12 \add After that,\add* \add the people of\add* Yehudah \add started bringing\add* a tenth of \add their\add* grain and wine and oil to the storerooms.\x + \xo 13:12: \xt Mal 3:10.\x*
\v 13 I appointed \add book-keepers\add* over the storerooms: the priest Shelemyah, the scribe Tsadok, and the Levite Pedayah with Hanan (the son of Zakkur, the son of Mattanyah) \add helping\add*. They were \add all\add* considered trustworthy, and \add their job included distributing the produce among their colleagues\add*.
\mi
\v 14 My God, remember me \add handling all these issues\add* and don’t wipe out my loyal kindness for \add your temple and its operation\add* \add that I’ve shown\add*.
\s1 The rest day
\p
\v 15 In those days I saw \add people\add* in Yehudah \add working\add* on the rest day—treading wine, bringing in grain, and loading donkeys, yes, even bringing wine, grapes, figs, and all kinds of loads into Yerushalem on the rest day. I \add complained to them when they were selling the goods\add*.\x + \xo 13:15: \xt Exo 20:8-10; Deu 5:12-14; Jer 17:21-22.\x*
\v 16 \add Also, people from Tsor\add* \add (Tyre)\add* were bringing in fish and all kinds of merchandise and were selling it on the rest day to the \add Israelis\add*, even in Yerushalem.
\v 17 I rebuked the Yehudah \add business leaders\add*, asking them, “What’s this evil thing that you’re all doing—profaning the rest day \add by treating it like a regular day\add*?
\v 18 \add Wasn’t that what your ancestors did—the very reason\add* our god brought all this evil on us and on this city? \add Now\add* you’re all \add making God angry with\add* Yisrael \add again\add* by profaning the rest day.”
\p
\v 19 \add So after that, when it started to get dark on Friday evenings, I ordered that the city gates be closed, and not to be opened until after the rest day\add*. I \add also stationed some of my young men to stand at the gates to ensure that no load could enter on the rest day\add*.
\v 20 \add Some traders and merchants selling various goods camped outside the city walls once or twice\add*,
\v 21 \add but I warned\add* them, “Why are you \add camping there outside\add* the wall? If you \add do it again, I’ll have you all removed\add*.” \add After that\add*, they \add no longer came on the rest days\add*.
\v 22 Then I told the Levites that they should purify themselves and then come to the gates to \add monitor them on the rest day\add*.
\mi My God, remember me \add having to deal with this, and show your amazing loyal faithfulness towards me\add*.
\s1 The scolding of marriage of foreigner
\p
\v 23 \add During that time\add*, I also saw Jews who’d \add married\add* women \add from Ashdod, Ammon, and Moav\add*,
\v 24 and half of their children spoke \add a foreign language from those other people groups\add* and \add couldn’t speak Hebrew\add*.
\v 25 \add So\add* I scolded \add those men\add* and cursed them and hit \add some of\add* them and pulled out their hair. Then I \add forced them to promise in front on God that they wouldn’t allow their daughters to marry foreign men, or their sons to take foreign wives\add*.
\v 26 \add I explained,\add* “Didn’t Yisrael’s \add own\add* King Shelomoh sin concerning that same matter? Among \add all the countries\add* \add in the world\add*, there wasn’t any other king like, and he was loved by his god who’d placed him \add there\add* as king over all Yisrael. \add But even then,\add* the foreign women caused him to sin.
\v 27 \add So do we need to\add* hear about all of you doing this terrible evil of being unfaithful to God by marrying foreign wives?”
\p
\v 28 \add Also\add* one of Yoyada’s sons (grandson of the high priest Elyashiv) was a son-in-law of Sanvallat the Horonite, \add so I banished him from my sight\add*.\x + \xo 13:28: \xt Neh 4:1.\x*
\mi
\v 29 My God, remember them for \add bringing shame to\add* the priesthood and \add dishonouring the vows made by\add* the \add priests\add* and the Levites.
\p
\v 30 Then I purified them from everything foreign, \add established regulations for each part of the work done by\add* the priests and the Levites,
\v 31 and \add organised the firewood supply at certain\add* times, \add including\add* for the first-fruits \add celebrations\add*.
\mi My God, remember me for good.
